-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: Kenya Electricity, Savannah Sugar Move
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 2010-11-17T16:38:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-17/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-kenya-electricity-savannah-sugar-move.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rallied for
a third day, climbing 0.7 percent to 1,922.56, by the 1:30 p.m.
close in Port Louis, the highest since March 2008.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index  was little changed at 84 by the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi from 84.02 yesterday, while Namibia’s
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  retreated for a third day, dropping
0.6 percent to 844.75 by the 5 p.m. in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock
Exchange All-Share Index  was also little changed at 6,810.10 by
the 1 p.m. close in Accra from 6,808.32 two days ago. The Ghana
exchange was closed for a public holiday yesterday. The  Nigerian 
market was closed today.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Electricity Generating Co.  (KEGC KN), the country’s
biggest electricity producer, climbed for a second day, rising
20 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 17.05 shillings. Kreditanstalt fuer
Wiederaufbau, Germany’s development bank, will lend Kenya 39.1
million euros ($52.8 million) to expand and build power plants,
the company said.  Savannah Sugar Estates Co.  (SAVA MP), a cane grower with
interests in property development, climbed 1 rupee, or 2
percent, to 51 rupees, the highest since Oct. 13. Shareholders
approved the issue of 26.3 million convertible preference shares
to existing shareholders at 40 rupees each and a change in the
company’s name to ENL Land Ltd.  Ghana Commercial Bank Ltd.  (GCB GN), the West African
nation’s biggest lender by branches, rose 5 pesewas, or 2.5
percent, to 2.05 cedis, the highest level since at least
February 1997, by the 1 p.m. close in the capital, Accra.  “Investors believe the bank has potential to earn more
profit in the last quarter,” Hilary Lomotey, a trader with
Renaissance Capital, spoke by phone from Accra. “We expect GCB
to post between a 15 and 20 percent full-year profit increase
over the previous year.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
